QUICK ACTIONS:
  - Edit Profile
  - Manage Subscription
  - Share UNJYNX (referral link)

ACCOUNT SECTION:
  - Connected Accounts (Google/Apple/Email indicators)
  - Timezone (auto-detected, editable)
  - Notifications Summary

BOTTOM:
  - Log Out
  - Delete Account (red, with 30-day grace period)


================================================================================
5. OFFLINE SYNC ENGINES
================================================================================

5.1 HOW THE BIG PLAYERS DO IT
-------------------------------

TODOIST - Incremental Sync Protocol:
- Custom Sync API (v9) with sync_token-based incremental updates
- sync_token="*" for full sync, subsequent tokens for deltas
- Resource-type filtering (sync only what you need)
- UUID-based command idempotency (safe retries)
- Rate limits: 1000 partial syncs / 15min, 100 full syncs / 15min
- Server is source of truth, client caches locally
- NOT true offline-first (requires eventual server confirmation)

NOTION - SQLite + CRDT Hybrid:
- SQLite cache on client for years (best-effort)
- Offline mode (launched Aug 2025) adds strong guarantees
- Downloads every record a page depends on for offline use
- lastDownloadedTimestamp tracking per page for incremental sync
- On reconnect: compares timestamps, fetches only newer pages
- Custom CRDT system for conflict resolution on non-text properties
- Handles structural changes (page moves, database row additions)

LINEAR - Local-First Sync Engine:
- IndexedDB on client, custom sync protocol
- All UI operations are instant (0ms latency, optimistic UI)
- Background sync pushes mutations to server
- Server processes linearly (total ordering)
- Client rebases on server state
- 3+ years of learnings from building sync engine
- Premium UX feel: everything feels instant

5.2 SYNC STRATEGY COMPARISON
------------------------------

| Strategy    | Complexity | Collaboration | Best For                    |
|-------------|------------|---------------|-----------------------------|
| LWW         | Low        | Poor          | Single-user, simple data    |
| Sync Tokens | Medium     | Moderate      | Client-server, API-based    |
| OT          | High       | Excellent     | Text editing (Google Docs)  |
| CRDT        | Very High  | Excellent     | P2P, multi-device, collab   |
| Replicache  | Medium     | Good          | Centralized server, web     |

5.3 RECOMMENDED APPROACH FOR UNJYNX
-------------------------------------

Primary strategy: Field-level LWW with Incremental Sync (already in ARCHITECTURE-PLAN)

Rationale:
- Single-user primary use case (not collaborative docs)
- LWW is sufficient for task CRUD operations
- Field-level (not row-level) prevents data loss on concurrent edits
- Incremental sync reduces bandwidth and battery usage
- Matches Todoist's proven approach

Implementation layers:
1. LOCAL: Drift (SQLite) as source of truth on device
2. SYNC: Custom sync protocol with sync_token pattern
3. CONFLICT: Field-level LWW with server timestamp authority
4. QUEUE: Offline mutation queue (persist across app restarts)
5. REALTIME: WebSocket for push updates when online

Future upgrade path:
- If team/collaboration features need it, upgrade to CRDT for shared projects
- PowerSync Open Edition as potential drop-in sync layer

5.4 FLUTTER-SPECIFIC SYNC LIBRARIES (2025-2026)
-------------------------------------------------

POWERSYNC (RECOMMENDED for evaluation):
- Package: powersync on pub.dev
- Syncs between SQLite (client) and PostgreSQL (server)
- Open Edition available (self-hosted)
- Official Drift integration via drift_sqlite_async
- LWW by default, customizable conflict resolution
- Works with custom backends (not just Supabase)
- Most mature Flutter offline-sync solution

SYNCABLE:
- GitHub: Mr-Pepe/syncable
- Offline-first multi-device sync for Flutter
- Referenced in project memory as a reference app
- Good for learning patterns, smaller community

OFFLINE_SYNC:
- Package: offline_sync on pub.dev
- Basic offline-first data management
- Auto-sync on connectivity restore
- Good for simple cases

BRICK (with offline_first adapter):
- Package: brick_offline_first
- ORM with offline-first capabilities
- Used with Supabase in production
- Less active community

CUSTOM (Drift + manual sync):
- Most control, most effort
- Drift for local DB (already in our stack)
- Custom sync service with mutation queue
- workmanager for background sync
- This is what UNJYNX should start with

RECOMMENDATION:
Start with Custom (Drift + manual sync) for Phase 1. Evaluate PowerSync Open Edition
for Phase 2+ when multi-device sync becomes critical. This avoids vendor lock-in while
keeping the upgrade path open.


================================================================================
6. WEBSOCKET PATTERNS FOR HONO
================================================================================

6.1 HONO WEBSOCKET OPTIONS
----------------------------

OPTION A: @hono/node-ws (RECOMMENDED)
- Package: @hono/node-ws v1.3.0
- Native Hono integration for Node.js
- Uses Web Standards WebSocket API
- Type-safe with Hono's TypeScript-first approach
- Lightweight, no additional dependencies

Setup pattern:
  import { createNodeWebSocket } from '@hono/node-ws'
  const app = new Hono()
  const { injectWebSocket, upgradeWebSocket } = createNodeWebSocket({ app })

  app.get('/ws', upgradeWebSocket((c) => ({
    onMessage(event, ws) { /* handle messages */ },
    onClose(event, ws) { /* cleanup */ },
    onOpen(event, ws) { /* setup */ },
  })))

  const server = serve({ fetch: app.fetch, port: 3000 })
  injectWebSocket(server)

OPTION B: Socket.IO with Hono
- More features (rooms, namespaces, auto-reconnect)
- Socket.IO has a PostgreSQL adapter (socket.io/docs/v4/postgres-adapter)
- Heavier, adds significant bundle size
- Better for complex multi-room scenarios
- Overkill for task sync notifications

OPTION C: Hono on Bun (native WebSocket)
- Bun has built-in WebSocket support
- Faster than Node.js WebSocket
- Less mature ecosystem
- Good future option if migrating to Bun

6.2 POSTGRESQL LISTEN/NOTIFY BRIDGE
--------------------------------------

Pattern: DB triggers fire NOTIFY > Node.js listener > WebSocket broadcast

Key library: pg-listen (github.com/andywer/pg-listen)
- Reliable PostgreSQL LISTEN/NOTIFY for Node.js
- Auto-reconnection
- JSON payload support

Architecture:

  [PostgreSQL]
      |
      | NOTIFY 'task_changes', '{"userId": "abc", "taskId": "123", "action": "update"}'
      |
  [pg-listen subscriber in Node.js]
      |
      | Filter by userId, find their WebSocket connection
      |
  [@hono/node-ws WebSocket server]
      |
      | ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'TASK_UPDATED', task: {...} }))
      |
  [Flutter client via web_socket_channel]

Database trigger example:

  CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION notify_task_change()
  RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
  BEGIN
    PERFORM pg_notify('task_changes', json_build_object(
      'user_id', NEW.user_id,
      'task_id', NEW.id,
      'action', TG_OP
    )::text);
    RETURN NEW;
  END;
  $$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

  CREATE TRIGGER task_change_trigger
  AFTER INSERT OR UPDATE OR DELETE ON tasks
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION notify_task_change();

6.3 RECOMMENDED UNJYNX WEBSOCKET ARCHITECTURE
-----------------------------------------------

Layer 1: @hono/node-ws for WebSocket server
Layer 2: pg-listen for PostgreSQL LISTEN/NOTIFY subscription
Layer 3: Connection manager (Map<userId, Set<WebSocket>>)
Layer 4: Message types (TASK_CREATED, TASK_UPDATED, TASK_DELETED, SYNC_REQUIRED)
Layer 5: Heartbeat/ping-pong for connection health (30s interval)
Layer 6: Reconnection logic on Flutter client (exponential backoff)

Flutter client: web_socket_channel package (dart:io WebSocket wrapper)

Why NOT Socket.IO:
- Adds ~100KB+ to bundle
- PostgreSQL adapter requires separate Redis-like pub/sub
- Hono's native WS helper is sufficient for our 1:1 notification model
- We don't need rooms/namespaces for personal task sync


================================================================================
7. FLUTTER ONBOARDING LIBRARIES
================================================================================

7.1 TOP PACKAGES RANKED
-------------------------

1. introduction_screen (RECOMMENDED - primary)
   - pub.dev: introduction_screen
   - Most popular onboarding package
   - Material 3 compatible (useMaterial3: true)
   - Customizable buttons (skip, next, done, back)
   - Uses dots_indicator internally
   - Supports custom page widgets
   - Supports Lottie/Rive animations in pages
   - Extensive customization (global styles, per-page overrides)
   - Active maintenance

2. smooth_page_indicator (RECOMMENDED - indicator component)
   - pub.dev: smooth_page_indicator
   - Best page indicator package (use WITH introduction_screen or custom)
   - 15+ built-in effects: Worm, Expanding Dots, Jumping Dot, Scrolling Dots,
     Slide, Scale, Swap, Color Transition, Customizable
   - Works with any PageView
   - Smooth animations
   - Fully customizable (size, color, spacing, shape)
   - Material 3 compatible

3. concentric_transition
   - pub.dev: concentric_transition
   - Beautiful circular clip transition between pages
   - Eye-catching, unique visual effect
   - Great for brand-forward onboarding
   - Works well with custom page layouts
   - Perfect for UNJYNX "break the satisfactory" brand feel

4. lottie (for onboarding animations)
   - pub.dev: lottie
   - Pure Dart Lottie player
   - Render After Effects animations natively
   - Perfect for onboarding hero illustrations
   - Combine with any onboarding scaffold

5. animated_onboarding_screen
   - pub.dev: animated_onboarding_screen
   - Uses Lottie for animations
   - Responsive design (adapts to screen sizes)
   - Customizable fonts, colors, animation sizes
   - Less popular but good for animation-heavy onboarding

6. flutter_intro
   - pub.dev: flutter_intro
   - Overlay/spotlight-style onboarding (post-main-screen)
   - Highlights UI elements with tooltips
   - Good for contextual onboarding AFTER initial screens
   - Use for the "first 3 sessions tooltip" pattern

7.2 RECOMMENDED UNJYNX ONBOARDING STACK
-----------------------------------------

Initial onboarding (first launch):
  - Build CUSTOM PageView (maximum control over brand experience)
  - smooth_page_indicator for dot indicators (ExpandingDots or WormEffect)
  - concentric_transition for page transitions (unique brand feel)
  - lottie for hero animations on each page
  - Total: 3 packages, fully custom layout

Post-onboarding contextual help:
  - flutter_intro for spotlight/tooltip overlays
  - Show on first 3 app launches, then stop
  - Highlight: Quick Add button, Project drawer, Reminder channel selector

Why NOT introduction_screen as scaffold:
  - For UNJYNX's brand-heavy, unique design, a custom PageView gives more control
  - introduction_screen is great for standard onboarding but constrains layout
  - However, if speed is priority in Phase 1, introduction_screen is a solid choice
  - Can always migrate to custom later

7.3 PACKAGE VERSIONS (check pub.dev for latest)
-------------------------------------------------

All packages below support null safety and Flutter 3.x:

| Package                    | Min Flutter | Material 3 | Notes                    |
|---------------------------|-------------|------------|--------------------------|
| introduction_screen       | 3.x         | Yes        | Most features out of box |
| smooth_page_indicator     | 3.x         | Yes        | Best indicator library   |
| concentric_transition     | 3.x         | Yes        | Unique visual effect     |
| lottie                    | 3.x         | N/A        | Animation renderer       |
| flutter_intro             | 3.x         | Yes        | Contextual overlays      |
| animated_onboarding_screen| 3.x         | Yes        | Lottie-integrated        |


================================================================================
SUMMARY OF RECOMMENDATIONS FOR UNJYNX
================================================================================

ONBOARDING:
  -> 5 screens, under 60 seconds
  -> Personalization questions (use case + reminder channel)
  -> Quick win (create first task)
  -> Custom PageView + smooth_page_indicator + concentric_transition + lottie
  -> Post-onboarding: flutter_intro for contextual tooltips

PROJECTS:
  -> Hierarchy: Folders > Projects > Sections > Tasks > Subtasks
  -> Areas (like Things 3) as top-level life categories
  -> Views: List (default) + Kanban board + Calendar
  -> 20+ colors + curated icon picker + emoji support
  -> Filters with boolean logic (AND/OR)
  -> Tags with colors, cross-project

SETTINGS:
  -> Grouped sections with dividers (Material 3 pattern)
  -> 8 groups: Account, Appearance, Notifications, Task Defaults,
     Integrations, Data & Privacy, Advanced, About
  -> Most used at top, advanced hidden
  -> Inline switches for toggles

PROFILE:
  -> Avatar + name + email + plan badge header
  -> Stats cards (streak, completed, weekly, daily avg)
  -> Connected accounts management
  -> Delete account with 30-day grace period (DPDP Act compliance)

OFFLINE SYNC:
  -> Phase 1: Custom Drift + manual LWW sync (Todoist-style sync tokens)
  -> Phase 2+: Evaluate PowerSync Open Edition
  -> Field-level LWW conflict resolution
  -> Offline mutation queue persisted to Drift
  -> Background sync via workmanager

WEBSOCKET:
  -> @hono/node-ws v1.3.0 for Hono WebSocket server
  -> pg-listen for PostgreSQL LISTEN/NOTIFY subscription
  -> Custom connection manager (userId -> Set<WebSocket>)
  -> web_socket_channel on Flutter client
  -> 30s heartbeat, exponential backoff reconnection

FLUTTER ONBOARDING:
  -> smooth_page_indicator (dot indicators)
  -> concentric_transition (page transitions)
  -> lottie (hero animations)
  -> flutter_intro (post-onboarding tooltips)
  -> Custom PageView scaffold for maximum brand control

